      "type": "html",
      "text": "Latin for \"(it) does not follow\". Applied to a statement that's supposed to be a logical consequent of a line of reasoning but in fact is not. Technically, a <i>non sequitur</i> is a superclass of many logical fallacies for which a putative consequent doesn't follow the precedent, such as [[Undistributed Middle]] and [[Argument By Analogy]], but use should be restricted to consequents that don't fall into another class. For example, in the argument: \"Socrates is a man and men are mortal, therefore Socrates is dead,\" the fragment \"Socrates is dead\" is a <i>non sequitur</i>. The greater the apparent randomness of a supposed consequent, the more likely to be accurate is the appellation.",
